## Interview Setting
Hallway bench between classes. Short window (he had 30 min before his next lab) but he was animated and gave me a lot of material in that time.

---

## Verbatim Quotes

### Quote 1
**Context:** Asked what tools he has tried to manage his coursework.

> "I tried a Telegram bot that scraped Moodle. I tried IFTTT. I tried a Notion template. I tried a calendar with reminders. I tried writing my own Python script. None of them lasted more than three weeks."

**What this tells us:** This is not someone who lacks technical skill or motivation. He has tried *more* solutions than the average student and they have *all* failed. The failure is not about the user — it is about the durability of any aggregation that requires maintenance.

---

### Quote 2
**Context:** Asked which one came closest to working.

> "The Python script. It actually scraped Moodle and sent me Telegram messages. But Moodle changed something in the login flow and it broke and I never fixed it. That was in October."

**What this tells us:** Even a self-built solution by a CS student fails because the upstream platform is unstable. Any third-party solution faces the same risk and will hit the same fate.

---

### Quote 3
**Context:** Asked what he does now.

> "Now I do nothing. I check Moodle when I remember. I miss things. It is what it is."

**What this tells us:** The trajectory is *learned helplessness*. He has gone from active builder to passive sufferer over the course of two semesters. This is the same endpoint as students who never tried anything — the system grinds everyone down to the same state.

---

### Quote 4
**Context:** Asked whether he would try again if someone built a better version.

> "I would install it. I would also expect it to break in three weeks. That is just what happens."

**What this tells us:** The trust deficit is real and earned. Any new solution starts in a hole. We have to budget for *proving* reliability, not just delivering features.

---

## Key Observations

- He listed five tools without hesitation. He had clearly thought about this before.
- Used the phrase "it is what it is" twice. That is the linguistic marker of a normalized chronic problem.
- Showed me the Telegram bot's last message — from October 2025. He had not deleted the chat. He just stopped expecting it to send anything.

---

## Preliminary Insights

- Even motivated, technical students cannot sustain their own solutions because Moodle's instability breaks scrapers.
- Tool fatigue is real: students who have tried and failed repeatedly are *less* likely to engage with new solutions, not more.
- The trust hole for any new solution in this space is deep. Reliability must be proven, not promised.

---

## JTBD Frame

"VG used to hire automation tools to do the job of staying on top of his courses. He has now hired *resignation* to do the same job. The functional job changed: he no longer expects to be on top of his courses, he expects to recover from missing things."

